speech.p: On a point of order, Mr Speaker. I apologise to you for attempting to raise it earlier, at an opportune moment, but I was so outraged by events that took place during our exchanges on the urgent question about shipbuilding on the Clyde that I became over-enthusiastic. In 20 years of teaching in a comprehensive school in Glasgow, I was never subjected to language such as that to which SNP Members were subjected by the hon. Member for Barrow and Furness (John Woodcock). May I ask you, Mr Speaker, how we should go about making an official complaint?
The Deputy Speaker then put forthwith the Questions necessary for the disposal of the business to be concluded at that time (Standing Order No.83F).
Government amendment (a) made in lieu of Lords amendment 84.
Government amendments (a) and (b) made in lieu of Lords amendment 85.
Lords amendments 61 to 83, 102 to 182 and 216 to 254 agreed to, with Commons financial privileges waived in respect of Lords amendments 117, 121, 125, 126, 158, 166, 227, 229, 235, 237, 239 and 243.
